In conclusion, this turn to the collective that the emergence of peer to peer represents does not
in any way present a loss of individuality, even of individualism. Rather it 'transcends and
includes' individualism and collectism in a new unity, which I would like to call 'cooperative
individualism'. The cooperativity is not necessarily intentional (i.e. the result of conscious
altruism), but constitutive of our being, and the best applications of P2P, are based on this
idea. Similar to Adam Smith's theory of the invisible hand, the best designed collaborative
systems take advantage of the self-interest of the users, turning it into collective benefit.

This recognition would help in distinguishing transformative P2P conceptions from regressive
interpretations harking back to premodern communion. I find this distinction well expressed
by Charlene Spretnak, cited by John Heron in a debate with the conception of an 'inclusional
self' by Ted Lumley of Goodshare.org:

