be separate things and possess many individual characteristics such as size, rate, and the direction of rotation, et
cetera. But careful scrutiny reveals that it is impossible to determine where any given whirlpool ends and the
river begins. Thus Bohm is not suggesting that the difference between 'things' is meaningless. He merely wants
